Pre-processing the Data¶

In [ ]:
del data['phish_detail_url']
del data['verified']
del data['online']
In [ ]:
data['time_difference'] = None
data['Submission_Year'] = None
data['Submission_Month'] = None

for i,j in data.iterrows():
  data.loc[i,'submission_time'] = data.loc[i,'submission_time'].split('+')[0]
  data.loc[i,'submission_time'] = datetime.strptime(data.loc[i,'submission_time'], '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S')
  data.loc[i,'Submission_Year'] = data.loc[i,'submission_time'].year
  data.loc[i,'Submission_Month']= data.loc[i,'submission_time'].strftime("%b")

  data.loc[i,'verification_time'] = data.loc[i,'verification_time'].split('+')[0]
  data.loc[i,'verification_time'] = datetime.strptime(data.loc[i,'verification_time'], '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S')
  data.loc[i,'time_difference'] = (data.loc[i,'verification_time'] - data.loc[i,'submission_time']).total_seconds()
data['time_difference'] = data['time_difference']/60

Question 2 - What are the top ten phishing target brands through this period. Identify a good visual for this analysis.¶

Only 1414 of the total rows have target brands, rest all have 'other' listed in the target column. As this is a small portion of the data, I have created the list of the existing brands and searched for these brands in each URL that has other in target column. This way I was able to capture more data.

A new column is added to dataframe i.e., brand which takes the value of target if there is a specific brand for that row. If the target is 'other' then based on the keyword search on the URL it outputs a company. By this way the data was incresead from 1414 to 3200

In [ ]:
company_list = data['target'].str.lower()
company_list = company_list.unique()
company_list = company_list[1:]
company_list[company_list == 'amazon.com'] = 'amazon'
company_list[company_list == 'pko polish bank'] = 'pko'
company_list = list(company_list)
company_list.append('royalmail')
company_list.append('llyod')
company_list.remove('ee')
In [ ]:
data['url'] = data['url'].str.lower()
data['brand'] = None
for i,j in data.iterrows():
  if data.loc[i,'target'].lower()=='other':
    for company in company_list:
      m = re.search(company,data.loc[i,'url'])
      if m and m.group(0)!=None:
        data.loc[i,'brand'] = m.group(0)
        break
  else:
    data.loc[i,'brand'] = data.loc[i,'target']
data['brand'] = data['brand'].str.capitalize()
brand_data = data.dropna()

Question 3 - How have phishing attacks trended over the year?¶

By Brands¶

I have taken top 5 brands from the above graph and observed how they performed each month of the year over the whole time period. There are five line graphs, one for each of those 5 companies.

In [ ]:
brand_data["Submission_Month_num"] = pd.to_datetime(brand_data.Submission_Month, format='%b', errors='coerce').dt.month
brand_data = brand_data.sort_values(by="Submission_Month")

colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'olive', 'brown']
a = 0
for i in ['Paypal', 'Google', 'Facebook', 'Royalmail', 'Amazon']:
  ref = brand_data[brand_data['brand'] == i].groupby(['Submission_Month',"Submission_Month_num"]).size().reset_index(name='counts')
  ref = ref.sort_values('Submission_Month_num')
  plt.plot(ref['Submission_Month'], ref['counts'], marker = 'x', markerfacecolor=colors[a], markersize=12, color= colors[a], linewidth=2, label = i)
  a += 1

plt.legend()
plt.legend(fontsize=20)
plt.xticks(fontsize=14)
plt.yticks(fontsize=14)
plt.gcf().set_size_inches(18.5, 10.5)
plt.gcf().set_size_inches(18.5, 10.5)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=18, weight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Number of Attacks', fontsize=18, weight='bold')
plt.title("Number of Phishing attacks happening over the year",fontname="Times New Roman",fontsize=24, fontweight="bold")
plt.show()

Again, as observed before there is a spike in number of attacks in the month of March. However, companies like Paypal and Google do not follow this trend

By Protocol¶

There are two protocols that I want to coduct my analysis on, these are HTTP and HTTPS

In [ ]:
protocol_data = data
protocol_data['Protocol'] = None
protocol_data['domain'] = None
protocol_data['domain_type'] = None

for i,j in protocol_data.iterrows():
  parse_object = urlparse(protocol_data.loc[i,'url'])
  protocol_data.loc[i,'Protocol'] = parse_object.scheme
  protocol_data.loc[i,'domain'] = parse_object.netloc
  protocol_data.loc[i,'domain_type'] = protocol_data.loc[i,'domain'].split(".")[-1]

By Method¶

Here I consider three major methods of targeting users, one by using login credentials, second by asking users to download a form and the last one by using a google form. I have used keyword searches such as 'login', 'docs.google' and 'download' in the URL to segregate them.

  • login - Stealing credentials
  • docs.google - Duping users by showing them a google form instead of actal page
  • download - Asking users to download something
In [ ]:
method_data = data
del method_data['brand']
method_data['method'] = None
for i,j in method_data.iterrows():
  if 'docs.google' in method_data.loc[i,'url'] :
    method_data.loc[i,'method'] = 'docs.google'
  if 'download' in method_data.loc[i,'url']:
    method_data.loc[i,'method'] = 'download'
  if 'login' in method_data.loc[i,'url']:
    method_data.loc[i,'method'] = 'login'
method_data = method_data.dropna()

My Hypothesis for Paypal being the top most attacked company is the fact that it is a financial service based application. Hackers can easily earn money if they can steal the credentials of users or dupe them to send money to a different account. So, users have to be extremely careful while doing an online transaction from any finacial service¶

plt.ylabel('Number of Attacks', fontsize=18, weight='bold')
plt.show()

From the year 2019 there have been more phishing attacks from the HTTPS websites than HTTP websites. However, it was contrary prior to the year 2019¶

Question 8 - What metrics would you like to design for this data?¶

  1. Mean Time to Detect (MTTD): What is the mean response time for your team to respond to a Phishing attack once they are aware of it? A great measure of the quality of your incident response plan implementation

  2. The number of brands that are attacked each year. It gives the range of companies that are affected by these Phishing scams.

  3. The number of Phishing attacks on a brand over-time. This metric indicates the effectiveness of the Cyber-security team in that particular brand.
